{
  "ADUs": {
    "A1": {
      "text": "The central thesis of the book is the ontological one that artworks are not physical objects on walls and filling spaces in museums, not sound structures indicated by composers and performed in concert halls, not linguistic structures 'uttered' by writers, but the actual 'performances' of artists that create such objects.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A2": {
      "text": "The correlative thesis concerning appreciation is that it requires that we relate the objects just mentioned (which are called the 'work-focus') with the performances that specify them.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A3": {
      "text": "Davies wishes to hold that artistic actions or performances, such as an artist executing a certain brushstroke at time t, 'might have transpired otherwise', in that his modal intuition is, for example, that the very same painting might have been painted at a somewhat different time from its actual time of execution.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "A4": {
      "text": "For on standard analyses of actions or events, the time at which they occur is one of their essential characteristics.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "A5": {
      "text": "Thus the normal sense in which it is true that Picasso could have painted a certain brushstroke later is the sense in which the relevant brushstroke action A, occurring at time t1, might not have existed or occurred at all, but instead some other brushstroke action B, of the same type as A, occurring at a later time t2 and having the same effect, might have existed.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A6": {
      "text": "But in this account there is no single action token such that it might have happened either at time t1 or at time t2 and hence no room for modally rich actions as such.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
